This thread isn't about Dire Charm. <br>
<br>
 It is about mages not wanting to return to the &quot;bad old days&quot; when our class almost went extinct due to uselessness.<br>
<br>
 It is about a class that was founded on offensive damage, is designed for offensive damage, and has a spellbook filled mostly with offensive damage spells, being unable to fulfill that role and instead being relegated to &quot;CoH Whore&quot; again like we were in Kunark/Velious, or more recently &quot;Rod Whore&quot; that much of Luclin has devolved into because our raid damage is not good enough to override the neccesity of T-Rodding others.<br>
<br>
When a nuking class is better off handing their mana to a non-nuking class so that *they can nuke instead*, there is a serious problem.<br>
<br>
Getting the sad &quot;upgrades&quot; that PoP test shows us will only magnify this since we aren't gaining power relative to the other classes.<br>
<br>
Let me put it very simply:<br>
<br>
**If PoP has Kunark/Velious Era resists that require Lures to land effective damage, mages will be pushed so deep into the &quot;rod whore&quot; role that the class will go back to the near extinction it suffered in those expansions.**<br>
<br>
Sage Finraziel <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usoulcraver.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Soulcraver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#333333>(9/21/02 3:08:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerrants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=335.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   The new mage</span><hr size=1> The only other class that has as much of a change as the mage class in the end game was the Necromancer.  They were no better than us and at times worse.<br>
<br>
Now with the changes to dot stacking and the number of buff slots increased they are back to where they want to be.  On my guild's boards they are giddy with the kind of damage they can output on boss mobs (since the fights last longer).  Raid leaders, seeing this power, now don't require them to twitch during fights unless it is absolutely positively necessary.  When is the last time a raid leader said.  &quot;Hey you know what, don't rod at all unless we absolutely need to.&quot;  Yes I rod before battles but between buffing/rebuffing/deaths and the like most of my time is spent rodding and not nuking.  Unless it is a weak mob then I get to nuke, but that is usually when we have overkill.<br>
<br>
All other classes do exactly what they do in normal exp grouping:<br>
<br>
-wizards nuke<br>
-melee fight<br>
-druids do what is necessary (i.e. utility)<br>
-enchanters buff and debuff<br>
-shaman buff and debuff<br>
-clerics heal<br>
-Necros deal long term damage (and do it well without pets)<br>
<br>
Now you can argue that other classes aren't as effective as they would like to be because of (insert what you want), but their role has changed.  If VI is listening, that is what sticks in the craw of most mages.  We want to be team players and win one for the gipper by doing what is necessary, but damn this is a game.  The object is to have as much fun at it as possible while you are accomplishing whatever it is you are trying to do.  <br>
<br>
That fun is derived from getting the perceived gratification out of the class that you select.  That perceived gratification comes from seeing how the class is described and then playing it and seeing how that matches up.  When that changes dramatically then the gratification and fun ceases or at the least is diminished.<br>
<br>
Therefore, whenever things are designed they must be designed with this in mind or people will never be happy.  Is the mage necessary?  Yes, in high level encounters you need those rods.  Can they be done by two boxing or having an alt mage log in coh/rod and then log out? Yes, it is done.  Is that how it should be?  Necessary but unfun?  <br>
<br>
People that choose melee (press A) or cleric (heal sit down-even that is changing with the new cleric spells but that is a different topic), do so knowing what they are getting into and have chosen that kind of game play.  Mages don't.  Please consider what we were/are/ and will be with the changes to come and ask yourselves; is this in line with how mages were developed?  And is the end game for mages supposed to change so dramatically with the turn of one spell (T-Rod)?  If it weren't for that one spell would mages, with their current spell line up be in demand like they are and as worth while to play in the end game?<br>
<br>
things to consider.<br>
<br>
<br>
